Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C and boil your #kettle{}. Carefully peel the skin off the @confit duck legs{2}. TIP: An easy way to do this is to slip a finger under the skin and ease it away from the flesh, then gently pull it off. Don't worry if it comes off in pieces! Remove and discard the skin, fat and grease. Pull the duck flesh off the bone into a #bowl{}. Shred roughly using two #forks{} or your fingers.

Pop the duck in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Tip in the @tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(finely chopped) and pour in the @water{75%ml} along with half the @chicken stock pot{1}. Grind in some @black pepper{} and bring to a simmer, stirring to dissolve the stock pot. Allow to simmer until thickened, ~{10-15%minutes}. Stir occasionally, then remove from the heat.

Meanwhile, mix the @water{50%ml} with the remaining stock pot. Melt the @unsalted butter{15%g} in a #small saucepan{} on medium heat and add the @plain flour{16%g}. Stir and cook (continuing to stir) for ~{2-3%minutes}. Gradually pour in all the @milk{189%ml} and stock, whisking all the time. Then bring to the boil (still whisking). The mixture will thicken as it boils. Remove from the heat and season with a @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{}.

Roughly chop the @basil{1%bunch}. Once the ragu is ready, stir in the basil. Lightly oil the bottom of an #ovenproof dish{} and lay in the first @lasagne sheets{3}. Snap one of the spare sheets to completely cover the base. Spoon a third of the ragu into the dish on top of the pasta layer, then drizzle over a third of the bechamel sauce. Sprinkle over a third of the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated) and place another sheet of pasta on top of the cheese.

Repeat these layers again using another third of the ragu, bechamel, hard Italian, followed by another layer of pasta. Spread the last third of ragu on top, drizzle over the remaining bechamel and sprinkle on any remaining hard Italian cheese. Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until you can easily stick a knife through the pasta and the top is golden, ~{25%minutes}.

Put the @Tenderstem® broccoli{1} on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}, a @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{}. When the lasagne has been cooking for 10-15 mins, pop the tenderstem in your oven for the last ~{15%minutes} of lasagne cooking time (check the broccoli after ~{10%minutes}). Meanwhile, finish your washing up! When ready, spoon the lasagne onto plates with a side of crispy tenderstem. Enjoy!